# NAT Gateway

Private subnets need **outbound** internet (updates, mirrors) but **no inbound**. A **NAT Gateway** delivers exactly that.

## What it is

- Managed, **sits in a public subnet**, holds an **Elastic IP**
- **Stateful** — outbound only; responses auto-allowed
- Auto-scales to **100 Gbps**; **hourly + per-GB** cost
- **No security group** can attach

## The HA caveat (exam favourite)

A NAT GW lives in **one AZ**. One NAT in AZ-a → if AZ-a fails, **all** private subnets lose internet, even in healthy AZs.

**Pattern: one NAT Gateway per AZ**, each private route table → its own.

*(NAT Instance = legacy; use the Gateway.)*
